The real Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story that is comparable to Moses leading the Israelites out of Egypt.
I grew up with this myth.
The myth is quickly told.
The young Communist Party and its three Red Armies were driven from their bases in the south by Chiang Kai-shek's nationalist government in the early 1930s.
Pursued and tormented by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, raging rivers, and treacherous wilderness, with Mao guiding the column to victory after victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of steadfastness, courage, and hope against unimaginably bleak prospects, the Red Armies reached northwest China.
Only a fifth of the 200,000 soldiers remained – exhausted, terribly wounded, but full of defiance.
A decade later, they retaliated, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and founded Mao's New China.
How much does China's founding myth correspond to reality?
In 2004, seventy years after the start of the Long March, I set out to search for its traces.
It is still a terrifying journey through regions that have changed little since today, inaccessible and incredibly poor.
Of the 40,000 survivors, perhaps only 500 are still alive today. I located 40 of them and interviewed them – they were ordinary people who had been left behind or had made it to the end, but their stories were extremely revealing.
Huan Zhiji was still a child, no bigger than his rifle, when he joined the Red Army.
He had no choice: His father had been arrested and would not be released until Huang agreed.
He thought of deserting, but stayed out of fear of being caught and shot.
Many ran away.
Six weeks after the start of the march, Mao's First Army of 86,000 had shrunk to 30,000 soldiers.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the Battle of the Xiang River, the first major engagement of the army on the march.
Yet no more than 15,000 died in the battle, the rest disappeared.
Another battle, at the Dadu River, is at the center of the legend of the Long March. Allegedly, 22 brave men overwhelmed a nationalist regiment guarding the Luding Bridge with machine guns, and cleared the way for the marching forces.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star Over China, that crossing the Dadu was the most significant event of the Long March, and it is still praised as such today.
Yet documents I have seen suggest that the general who led the division across the Dadu first told the party historians a completely different story. "The matter was not as complicated as people later made it out to be," he said. "When examining historical facts, one should respect the truth."
How one presents it is another matter.
The legend lives on.
There was merely a skirmish above the Dadu River.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, allowed Mao to pass.
As a reward, he later received a ministerial post in the communist government.
The march participants did not know where they were going.
There were constant discussions about the final destination.
When they gathered in North China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the march.
But the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could barely feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the icy cold.
Women were ordered to turn around and go back home because there was not enough food.
A little over a month after the unification of the three Red Armies, the Party decided that the Long March had to continue.
Yet she was saved by the kidnapping of Chiang Kai-shek by the General, whom Chiang had sent to destroy the Communists.
As part of the price for his release, Chiang recognized the Communists as legitimate.
The Long March was over.
But not for the 21,000 men and women of the Western Legion.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's archrival, and had the mission to cross the western Chinese border to seek help from Russia.
Yet Mao sent them conflicting orders, so that they could neither fight nor retreat.
Trapped on barren land, where survival was difficult, they were wiped out by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border, the rest were killed or captured.
It was the Red Army's greatest defeat.
Yet it is absent from official historical records.
A Muslim commander took the leading officer Wang Quanyan as his mistress.
This was enough to make her in the eyes of the Party a traitor and to deny all the years she had devoted to the army.
She and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for a half-century to be recognized as participants in the march.
The participants of the Long March were steadfast, fought, starved, despairing, and persevered.
Hunger led the soldiers to take hostages in order to extort ransom.
Massacres continued until practically no officers were left to command in the battles.
When the marchers had doubts, they overcame them through communist propaganda.
They endured their martyrdom with a bravery and self-sacrifice that is unmatched in the history of China and other peoples.

What drove her to do that?
I interviewed one of the top generals about what he knew about communism at the time. "I had no idea then, just as I don't now," he answered. "I even doubt that Mao himself really knew what it was." For him, who had survived extreme poverty and oppression, communism was a beautiful dream that kept him alive, the hope for a just and progressive society.
No one perhaps – or could – know how much suffering was still to come, how great the sacrifice and how enormous the difference between the dream and reality would be.
